An American, Two Classes of Citizens
New York — At the time I'm writing this article, officials across the United States are still tallying the votes from the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the final results are confirmed, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This is to be expected in a fiercely competitive election with record-breaking voter turnout.
Only American citizens are allowed to vote in the presidential election, but this choice affects people in various places.
If it's said that determining the election result is too early now, then discussing the implications of this election on the world's most powerful country is not too early.
From a positive perspective, the United States is still a strong democratic country.
Despite being actually restricted by the COVID-19 pandemic, the voter participation rate is still very high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
And violent events are rare.
The court is investigating the decision of the United States Postal Service, which seems to be made with a political motive, to interfere with the delivery of ballots from areas where the votes are mainly expected to come from the Democratic Party.
President Trump, the incumbent president of the United States, made a baseless declaration of victory on Tuesday evening, which almost received no response, and his request to stop counting (at least in the states where he is leading) seems to be ignored.
However, it is worrying that the division among American voters remains very large.
The votes of the two candidates are almost equal.
Of course, this division is likely to lead to the division of the government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The governor and state legislature seats are almost evenly divided between the two parties (Republicans have a slight advantage).
The Democratic Party's expected "blue wave" has not been realized.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote with a large margin, probably winning around 4-5 million votes out of nearly 160 million votes.
However, Republicans have held onto many seats that were predicted to flip, and Democrats have actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result is also not based on hard data, nor is it a result of a political adjustment.
Trump's poll situation is very good, with 50 million more votes than in 2016, making it the second most votes gained by a US presidential candidate in history, and exceeding any winning candidate before him.
Notably, this is happening in a context of a record-high 100,000 new COVID-19 cases and over 1,000 deaths every day.
It's worth noting that nearly half of voters switched to support him at a time when the consequences of his government's mishandling of the virus have become most severe.
Even if Trump loses, which seems quite possible, he will still have a strong voice, especially if he continues to stay in the public eye (which also seems possible).
Even if he himself does not participate in the election, he will still have a significant impact on the choice of the Republican Party's nominee in the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican Party would be quite far from the party of George W. Bush or Ronald Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
Not surprisingly, although Trump has no evidence, he has been working hard to show himself to be noble and upright, and has been trying to make the election results invalid and accuse of voting irregularities.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept the legitimacy of Biden as president.
Trump may never concede, let alone attend the inauguration ceremony of the successor.
Quoting Will Rogers, Trump has never encountered a rule he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They divided themselves into different communities and regions based on similar viewpoints.
Each world tends to watch its own cable channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
While the lack of the civic course has provided a convenience for the division of different age groups.
It's worth emphasizing that the division of the country is not drawn along economic lines in most cases.
Both classes of people voted for the two candidates, and voting patterns by population, gender, and race do not seem to be one-sided as many people predicted.
Their differences are mainly in the measures of relief.
Education level is obviously an indicator of political orientation, and geography is also the case. Republican voters tend to live in suburbs and rural areas, while Democrats tend to live in major cities.
However, culture may play a larger role in American politics than any other factor.
Indeed, foreign policy seems not to be an important issue in the campaign, except to mobilize specific constituencies, such as large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
It is difficult to get public support for major reforms of the presidential election process or the way government operates in such a context.
This situation is similar to the UN Security Council reform.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform, because any potential solution will benefit some people while harming others.
It's not surprising that those who will suffer a loss due to the reform will resist the reform.
This will make governance more difficult.
This largely depends on the Republican leader of the Senate, Mitch McConnell, and his ability and willingness to collaborate with the future Biden administration.
Collaboration also requires Biden to make concessions, which will undoubtedly be resisted by members of his own party who are strong in ideology.
Democrats have tried to sharply deny everything represented by Trump.
But they failed.
While Republicans sought an election that would validate Trump.
But even this did not come to fruition as they had hoped.
On the contrary, the election revealed a country and two classes of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
